      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f692f1c227e412b0",
      "text": "The spread of learning algorithms is changing the meaning and forms of prediction, affecting the image of the future and the way to deal with it in the present. Whereas in the current view, the future is seen as open and unknowable because it does not yet exist and depends on present actions and expectations, today’s predictive algorithms claim to foresee the future. This claim is both exciting and frightening. It may lead to optimization of the use of resources and to targeted and effective prevention and planning, yet also may bind the future with preemptive policies based on existing patterns. In any case, it breaks with the current idea of the future and management of uncertainty. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5a3edfcbc954c9b1",
      "text": "[[Elena Esposito]]'s point in this chapter is that algorithmic prediction is very different from the idea of prediction that has established itself in modern society since the eighteenth century, oriented and guided by the [[Calculus of Probability]]; that is, it differs from the mathematical treatment of chance that began with the work of Blaise Pascal and Pierre de Fermat in the second half of the seventeenth century. Whereas probability calculus offers a rational way to deal with uncertainty, algorithms claim to provide an individual score for individual persons or singular events. [⇒ [[Event (Ereignis)]]]"
